Medical Report 

Patient: Mrs. Alena Bank, born on March 25, 1978, residing at Tulpenweg 3, 10115 Berlin, 
patient number 235987, was admitted to our practice for a cholecystectomy due to 
symptomatic cholelithiasis. 

History:  
Mrs. Bank complained of recurrent right upper quadrant abdominal pain, particularly after 
fatty meals. Other symptoms included nausea and occasional vomiting. The symptoms had 
intensified over the last few weeks. 

Findings:  
An ultrasound examination of the abdomen confirmed multiple gallstones with signs of 
gallbladder inflammation. There were no signs of bile duct stones or pancreatitis. 

Diagnosis:  
Symptomatic cholelithiasis. 

Treatment:  
A laparoscopic cholecystectomy was performed to remove the gallbladder. The operation 
proceeded without complications, and Mrs. Bank recovered well from the procedure. 

Follow-up:  

Postoperative controls are planned to monitor the healing process and ensure that no 
further complications occur. Mrs. Bank is advised to adjust her diet to prevent future 
gallbladder problems. 

Recommendations:  
Mrs. Bank is advised to follow a low-fat diet and regularly undergo follow-up examinations in 
our practice to monitor her overall health status and minimize the risk of further gall-related 
complaints. 

Kind regards,
